=> What is the Problem with Traditional switch?
    -> Before Java Pattern Matching, switch was mainly used with:
        - Primitive types (int, char, etc.)
        - String
        - Enum types
        - constants

        -> Example: refer SwitchExample.java

    -> So traditional switch work using exact value match. And this is the main problem with traditional switch. 
    -> It cannot work with complex data types or patterns. It can only work with exact values. 

    -> This is where Pattern Matching with switch comes into play. 
    -> It allows us to use patterns in switch statements, making it more powerful and flexible.
        -> In switchExample.java, we can see that we are using pattern matching with switch to check the type of the object and then perform some action based on the type.
            -> case String s -> System.out.println("It's a String: " + s);
            -> case Integer i -> System.out.println("It's an Integer: " + i);

            -> In this case String s -> contains two things:
                -> String: The type we want to match (String)
                -> s: A variable (s) that will hold the value if the match is successful.
                -> So if the object is of type String, it will be assigned to the variable s and we can use it in the case block.
                -> if obj is of type Integer, it will be assigned to the variable i and we can use it in the case block.
                -> if obj is none of the above types, it will go to the default case and print "Unknown type".

            -> so if we define pattern matching with switch:
                -> first we check the type of the object (String, Integer, etc.)
                -> if the type matches, we can use the variable (s, i, etc.) to perform some action based on the type.

    -> This is a powerful feature because it allows us to write more concise and readable code when dealing with complex data types and patterns.
    -> Some other example code:
        
        public class SwitchExample {
            public static void main(String[] args) {
                Shape shape = new Circle(5);
                String result = switch (shape) {
                    case Circle c -> "It's a circle with radius: " + c.radius();
                    case Rectangle r -> "It's a rectangle with width: " + r.width() + " and height: " + r.height();
                    default -> "Unknown shape";
                };
            }
        }

    -> Advance part of pattern matching with switch:
        -> When Clause
            -> This allows us to add additional conditions to the case labels.
            -> Example:
                case String s when s.length() > 5 -> System.out.println("It's a long string: " + s);
                case String s when s.length() <= 5 && s.length() > 0 -> System.out.println("It's a short string: " + s);
            -> You can add multiple conditions inside the when clause using: &&, ||, etc.
            -> Java first check pattern match and then evaluate the when clause. 
            -> So if the pattern match fails, it will not evaluate the when clause.

        -> Pattern label Dominance
            -> When multiple case labels can match the same input, the most specific pattern is chosen.
            -> For example, if you have a case for a specific type and a case for a more general type, the case for the specific type will be chosen if it matches.
            -> Example:
                case Number n -> System.out.println("It's a number: " + n);
                case Integer i -> System.out.println("It's an integer: " + i);
                -> In this case, if the input is an Integer, it will match both cases (Number and Integer), but the case for Integer will be chosen because it is more specific.

        -> Scope of Pattern Variables and switch
            ->  The scope of pattern variables is limited to the case block in which they are defined.
            -> This means that you cannot use a pattern variable outside of the case block where it is defined.
            -> Example:
                case String s -> {
                    System.out.println("It's a string: " + s);
                }
                // System.out.println(s); // This will cause a compile-time error because s is not in scope here.
        -> Null case labels
            -> You can use null as a case label to match null values.
            -> Example:
                case null -> System.out.println("It's null");
            -> This allows you to handle null values in a more concise and readable way.

        -> Example code for all the above features can be found in "AdvancedPatternMatchingSwitch.java" file.

=> Pattern Match with instanceof:
    -> Before Java 21, we had to use instanceof to check the type of an object and then cast it to the appropriate type before using it. 
    -> With pattern matching for instanceof, we can combine the type check and the cast into a single operation. 
    -> In example "PatternMatchingInstanceOfExample.java", we are using pattern matching with instanceof to check the type of the object and then perform some action based on the type. 
    -> This is more concise and readable than the traditional way of using instanceof and casting.

=> Type Patterns:
    -> Type patterns are a new feature in Java 21 that allows us to match the type of an object in a switch statement. 
    -> This is similar to pattern matching with instanceof, but it is used in switch statements instead of if statements. 
    -> In example "SwitchExample.java", we are using type patterns in the switch statement to check the type of the object and then perform some action based on the type. 
    -> This is more concise and readable than the traditional way of using switch statements with exact value matches.

    -> There are basically three types of patterns in Java 21:
        -> Type pattern with reference type (e.g., String s)
            -> Example code:
                case String s -> System.out.println("It's a string: " + s);
                case Integer i -> System.out.println("It's an integer: " + i);

        -> Type pattern with primitive type (e.g., int i)
            -> Example code:
                case int i -> System.out.println("It's an integer: " + i);
                case char c -> System.out.println("It's a character: " + c);

        -> Type pattern with parameterized type (e.g., List<String> list)
            -> Example code:
                case List<String> list -> System.out.println("It's a list of strings: " + list);
                case Map<String, Integer> map -> System.out.println("It's a map of string to integer: " + map);

        -> Example code for all the above features can be found in "TypePatternExamples.java" file.

=> Record Patterns:
    -> Record patterns are a new feature in Java 21 that allows java to:
        -> check whether object is a record type
        -> automatically extract record component values
        -> avoid manual accessor method calls

    -> This is similar to pattern matching with instanceof, but it is used for records instead of regular classes.                 
    -> In example "RecordPatternExample.java", we are using record patterns in the if statement to check the components of a record and then perform some action based on the values of those components. 
    -> This is more concise and readable than the traditional way of using if statements with exact value matches for records.
